dible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\n\n\n[defendant] D-4 Times of India adverse fact check\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\nAuthor/source line: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST\n\nRelevant extracted text from fetched page:\n\nClavicular is trending again, and this time it is about a rumor that spread very fast online. The 20-year-old streamer, whose real name is Braden Peters, was suddenly at the center of claims that he is expecting his first child. The story sounded shocking, people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her. The claim picked up millions of views and quickly moved across social media. Many users were confused.\n\nSome even believed it at first because Clavicular had recently said he wants to become a father soon. But when people looked closely, things did not add up. There was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update. At the same time, Clavicular has been dealing with serious real-life issues. He was recently hospitalized after collapsing during a livestream. His publicist also left him, saying he needs to take his health more seriously.\n\n