{"type":"message_update","assistantMessageEvent":{"type":"toolcall_start","contentIndex":1,"partial":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have now reviewed the admitted record. Here is my analysis of the key evidence:\n\n**Market Rule (PX-1/D-1):** The market resolves Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between April 20, 2026 and Dec 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Only credible announcements qualify; jokes do not suffice. Resolution source is statements from Clavicular or representatives, but a \"definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\"\n\n**Plaintiff's Evidence:**\n- **Forbes extraction (PX-6/ev_2c388df1):** Forbes characterized the dispute as being over \"what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant.\" Also notes \"market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes.\"\n- **Gamma API (PX-7/ev_b08e7634):** Shows final Yes outcome with outcome prices [1, 0], resolved May 1, 2026.\n\n**Defense's Evidence:**\n- **Times of India fact-check (PX-8/D-4/ev_c30009):** \"No video confirms a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirms it.\" Identifies the viral claim as a rumor about a girlfriend pregnant after 10 days. States the actual livestream remarks were: \"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\" Concludes \"there is no confirmed pregnancy\" and the viral claim is \"false.\"\n- **Hindustan Times (D-5/ev_519a3b6f):** Reports Clavicular proposed a contest where 500 women would compete in a beauty pageant, with the winner impregnated by him. Quotes: \"I must have children. I must get children today\" and \"I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\"\n- **Express Tribune (D-6/ev_115037a4):** Same contest reporting, quotes: \"I must have children. I must get children today\" and \"I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\"\n\n**Analysis:**\n- The rule requires a **credible announcement** that Clavicular **and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy**.\n- The preserved primary sources (Hindustan Times, Express Tribune, Times of India) all describe Clavicular making **future-oriented statements** about wanting children and proposing a pregnancy contest. These are explicitly characterized as shock content/controversial proposals, not as confirmations of an existing partner pregnancy.\n- The Forbes fragment is the only source pointing to a \"gotten a girl pregnant\" statement, but it is a partial extraction from a metered page with explicit limitations. It does not preserve the full context, original clip, or source chain. Critically, Forbes itself acknowledges the market description and platform clarification said **No**, creating conflict.\n- The Gamma API's event metadata describes the narrative as driven by \"repeated public vows to become a father,\" \"fertility stack reveal,\" and \"controversial pitch for a 'dating show' to select a baby mama\" - again, future aspiration and stunt, not confirmation.\n- The Times of India fact-check explicitly states **no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy** and **no video confirmed it**. This directly addresses the credited announcement requirement.\n\n**Conclusion:** The preponderance of admitted evidence shows Clavicular made provocative remarks about wanting children and proposing a pregnancy contest, but there is no credible preserved announcement that he and a partner were **already** expecting a baby through pregnancy. The Forbes fragment is insufficient without the missing source chain, and the fuller preserved reporting contradicts the proposition.\n\nTherefore, the proposition is **not demonstrated**."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"hMRxOtkFF","name":"mcp","arguments":{},"partialArgs":"","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","mode